solution: ```class CountIntervals {
    set<pair<int,int>> st;
    int tot = 0;
public:
    CountIntervals() {}

    void add(int left, int right) {
        auto it = st.lower_bound({left, -1});
        if (it != st.begin() && prev(it)->second >= left) --it;
        while (it != st.end() && it->first <= right) {
            int l = it->first, r = it->second;
            tot -= r - l + 1;
            left = min(left, l);
            right = max(right, r);
            it = st.erase(it);
        }
        st.insert({left, right});
        tot += right - left + 1;
    }

    int count() {
        return tot;
    }
};
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log N) per add, O(1) per count
space complexity: O(N)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Uses a balanced BST to store disjoint intervals and keeps a running total of covered integers. Each add merges overlapping/adjacent intervals in logarithmic time and updates the total in constant time; count simply returns the pre-computed total.

